<subSubSection id="82F34D11588EA588315627A3C51DDD43" type="description">
<paragraph id="13EC80E1C53B41C64A930DCBDE7E33D2" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="D601CBC5ECF6321183B523C00413A506" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
Adult (Figs 
<figureCitation id="6D516346A153F18C3D39B8BA15865561" captionStart="Figures 2, 3" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 2, 3. Lyonetia ledi adults resting on leaves of Rhododendron ferrugineum (Switzerland, Graubuenden, Ardez)." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.5.76930.figures2-3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/612940" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="2B029240DB7BFCB04C84BA85A55BE08B" captionStart="Figures 2, 3" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 2, 3. Lyonetia ledi adults resting on leaves of Rhododendron ferrugineum (Switzerland, Graubuenden, Ardez)." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.5.76930.figures2-3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/612940" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Head, tuft, and eye-cap as well as thorax glossy white; labial palpus white with some fuscous on outer surface; antenna about length of forewing, pale grey. Wingspan c. 7-9 mm; forewings glossy white; short oblique dark brown streak from tornus at half-length of wing, longitudinal patch at about 2/3, two dorsal streaks from tornus converging in disc at 3/4; large ochre-brown patch in distal fifth; costal ciliae with four blackish strigulae, large black apical dot followed by black line and apical scale-pencil. Hindwings grey. The variation of forewing markings is considerable, i.e. a short sub-basal streak below fold at about 1/5 or a complete medial streak as figured by 
<bibRefCitation id="966BAF1212A21291C10BE902E8054966" author="Bengtsson, BA" journalOrPublisher="ArtDatabanken, SLU, Uppsala" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" refId="B3" refString="Bengtsson, BA, Johansson, R, 2011. Nationalnyckeln till Sveriges flora och fauna. Fjaerilar: Bronsmalar-rullvingemalar. Lepidoptera: Roeslerstammiidae-Lyonetiidae. ArtDatabanken, SLU, Uppsala" title="Nationalnyckeln till Sveriges flora och fauna. Fjaerilar: Bronsmalar-rullvingemalar. Lepidoptera: Roeslerstammiidae-Lyonetiidae." year="2011">Bengtsson and Johansson (2011)</bibRefCitation>
could not be observed, whereas the medial and postmedial markings are completely reduced in one specimen.
</paragraph>
<caption id="358C8E934F6E4B2825B7FF27ECB4D23A" doi="10.3897/alpento.5.76930.figures2-3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/612940" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" start="Figures 2, 3" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="D1A9A4406812072A007BE804F4003E19" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="DA7785133983062DEE5847AD71B83093" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Figures 2, 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="CA2D309D52784DAE0D3DD62B77313073" authorityName="Wocke" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Lyonetiidae" genus="Lyonetia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lyonetia ledi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ledi">
<emphasis id="31D2106A803A93A794814D8CA808AD47" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Lyonetia ledi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
adults resting on leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="83A81FC2674411EF94BBE5D8D1792A55" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Rhododendron" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rhododendron ferrugineum" order="Ericales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ferrugineum">
<emphasis id="4ACDF3880EC2A1AA4213E695BC632FE8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Rhododendron ferrugineum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Switzerland, 
<normalizedToken id="51DA9D17D6577050A75FE083D70D02F2" originalValue="Graubünden">Graubuenden</normalizedToken>
, Ardez).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8702AAA298C51D6BF47A697781CA2D9F" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
For exhaustive description of the adults including genitalia of both sexes see 
<bibRefCitation id="DC52FD6DE1F9F013A280B7842964F92F" author="Bengtsson, BA" journalOrPublisher="ArtDatabanken, SLU, Uppsala" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" refId="B3" refString="Bengtsson, BA, Johansson, R, 2011. Nationalnyckeln till Sveriges flora och fauna. Fjaerilar: Bronsmalar-rullvingemalar. Lepidoptera: Roeslerstammiidae-Lyonetiidae. ArtDatabanken, SLU, Uppsala" title="Nationalnyckeln till Sveriges flora och fauna. Fjaerilar: Bronsmalar-rullvingemalar. Lepidoptera: Roeslerstammiidae-Lyonetiidae." year="2011">Bengtsson and Johansson (2011)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2CB02BFD8B14DBDF1E5059FC12A07469" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="701BB3D8D11A197214A6541C02F00450" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="0ADB2307988E2A95872DFAE8B3C47556" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Biology.</emphasis>
In Europe, 
<taxonomicName id="82C81852D39178B6FB438237DC694EEE" authorityName="Wocke" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Lyonetiidae" genus="Lyonetia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lyonetia ledi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ledi">
<emphasis id="451070671F664D553A2BAE391BB85CB5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Lyonetia ledi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a widespread leaf-miner of 
<taxonomicName id="F54D7D2E688F329F8E4A6644D41FF441" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Rhododendron" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rhododendron tomentosum" order="Ericales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tomentosum">
<emphasis id="3D95C1D0E8373BD674798D035D5F686B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Rhododendron tomentosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="CD2BAD02EC0992C67FB9009C139FD906" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Rhododendron" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Ericales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Ericaceae</taxonomicName>
), but in the northern part of the continent it is also regularly recorded from the unrelated 
<taxonomicName id="EA2059412BF26F88DEFBF90887012333" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myricaceae" genus="Myrica" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Myrica gale" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gale">
<emphasis id="3C8ABD603DF211951CBC1EA9F1665C38" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Myrica gale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="5C141D71A0426C9BAF07F4E918C2A181" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myricaceae" genus="Myrica" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Myricaceae</taxonomicName>
), a species absent from large parts of Central Europe. Larvae of the newly discovered population from the Engadine mine the leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="1AD4EEEA719B86C3852A6E68C612FA1E" class="Insecta" genus="R." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="R. ferrugineum" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ferrugineum">
<emphasis id="B2F6EB38D816CDF7612FF04B5467E654" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">R. ferrugineum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The egg is laid on the upper side of a leaf. The tunnel-mine initially extends towards the base of the leaf, then turns and continues alongside the leaf rim towards the leaf tip, where a spacious blotch mine is formed. Only current year leaves, recognizable by their green underside are infested, while older leaves with the plant's name-giving rusty underside may contain mines from previous years only (Figs 
<figureCitation id="CE6B5BF8858FAFC65E420B4C408742FF" captionStart="Figures 4, 5" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 4, 5. Leaf-mines of Lyonetia ledi on Rhododendron ferrugineum (Switzerland, Graubuenden, Ardez)." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.5.76930.figures4-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/612941" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="C30AC0AEC4891690A59A9C5BC08B3413" captionStart="Figures 4, 5" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 4, 5. Leaf-mines of Lyonetia ledi on Rhododendron ferrugineum (Switzerland, Graubuenden, Ardez)." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.5.76930.figures4-5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/612941" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">5</figureCitation>
). The mine is hardly visible on the underside. Frass is firstly deposited in continuous line which later fills the complete tunnel-mine, whereas it is deposited in irregular flawy patches in the botch-mine. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="200D22A31EE5B1B31FC582BF3B4794A1" author="Kuroko, H" journalOrPublisher="Esakia" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" pagination="1 - 61" refId="B11" refString="Kuroko, H, 1964. Revisional studies on the family Lyonetiidae of Japan (Lepidoptera). Esakia 4: 1 - 61" title="Revisional studies on the family Lyonetiidae of Japan (Lepidoptera)." volume="4" year="1964">Kuroko (1964)</bibRefCitation>
frass may also be ejected through semicircular lateral slits along the border of the blotch mine on the lower side. The same author also reports the larva moving to a new leaf and starting to produce a new mine, an observation unconfirmed in alpine habitats. The final instar larva is light yellow with a light brown head and a brownish mottled thoracic shield and ca. 4.8 mm long (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F93FEB8876935919F042DC8BBDC8BEC5" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 6. Final instar larva of Lyonetia ledi on Rhododendron ferrugineum (Switzerland, Graubuenden, Ardez)." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.5.76930.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/612942" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">6</figureCitation>
). On the underside of a nearby leaf, it constructs a X-shaped silken scaffold in the center of which it then pupates like in a hammock (Figs 
<figureCitation id="3E73F2AD0D2816F3594820EB9F546F96" captionStart="Figures 7, 8" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 7, 8. Characteristic cocoon with final instar larva and pupa of Lyonetia ledi on Rhododendron ferrugineum (Switzerland, Graubuenden, Ardez)." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.5.76930.figures7-8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/612943" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">7</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="B5455175B0F40DE4017A1E12B134ACA9" captionStart="Figures 7, 8" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 7, 8. Characteristic cocoon with final instar larva and pupa of Lyonetia ledi on Rhododendron ferrugineum (Switzerland, Graubuenden, Ardez)." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.5.76930.figures7-8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/612943" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">8</figureCitation>
). The ca. 4.4 mm long pupa can be easily found when examining the underside of mined or adjacent leaves. First larvae were detected on the 29th of July 2021, two weeks later on the 12th of August 2021 only pupae were found. In captivity the adults emerged after about a week to 10 days between 6th and 21st of August. These data suggest hibernation of the adults as it is also reported from Sweden, with a flight period lasting from mid-August to October and again from April to May (
<bibRefCitation id="318B4A4F862D8041A8D66338A62DB42E" author="Bengtsson, BA" journalOrPublisher="ArtDatabanken, SLU, Uppsala" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" refId="B3" refString="Bengtsson, BA, Johansson, R, 2011. Nationalnyckeln till Sveriges flora och fauna. Fjaerilar: Bronsmalar-rullvingemalar. Lepidoptera: Roeslerstammiidae-Lyonetiidae. ArtDatabanken, SLU, Uppsala" title="Nationalnyckeln till Sveriges flora och fauna. Fjaerilar: Bronsmalar-rullvingemalar. Lepidoptera: Roeslerstammiidae-Lyonetiidae." year="2011">Bengtsson and Johansson 2011</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
