<paragraph id="526DB895254481BAE43087C74E336FF7" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
The larvae seem to be regularly infested by parasitic wasps of 
<taxonomicName id="6705482993F26A27F6DBD4DC8C7838FE" baseAuthorityName="Hellen" baseAuthorityYear="1949" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Diadegma" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diadegma semiclausum" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="semiclausum">
<emphasis id="8FE4D5375BDAFF94F80A073785DCB596" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Diadegma cf. semiclausum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, (
<taxonomicName id="2962DB55348103BD7D095A7591718135" family="Ichmeumonidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" rank="family">Ichmeumonidae</taxonomicName>
) (barcoded) and an unidentified species of 
<taxonomicName id="EF8F8603C9F5EB0A7A7915EFCBEB655D" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ichneumonidae</taxonomicName>
as we found a number of their cocoons that were already empty.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9811E3B871F63A60BAB74A3A68E52FB3" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="19F9ECDEB02657AAF90DA9AA0C376101" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
Habitat (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="FAD4A3BC71BC12F9ACE4500841F96AB4" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 9. Habitat of Lyonetia ledi in Engadine / Switzerland with Rhododendron ferrugineum." figureDoi="10.3897/alpento.5.76930.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/612944" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">9</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="1D013BB6067C1F61960FB48647B4B7E8" authorityName="Wocke" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Lyonetiidae" genus="Lyonetia" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lyonetia ledi" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ledi">
<emphasis id="FD07BA0A85C408AC99C794D1DBE99FDF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Lyonetia ledi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considered as a tyrphobiontic species (
<bibRefCitation id="57E636660C1662C22962827320BD6782" author="Spitzer, K" journalOrPublisher="Zeitschrift der Arbeitsgemeinschaft oesterreichischer Entomologen" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" pagination="87 - 97" refId="B17" refString="Spitzer, K, Jaros, J, Lichtenberger, F, Malicky, H, 1996. Die Biodiversitaet der Puergschachenmoores im steirischen Ennstal und ihr Schutzwert. Zeitschrift der Arbeitsgemeinschaft oesterreichischer Entomologen 48: 87 - 97" title="Die Biodiversitaet der Puergschachenmoores im steirischen Ennstal und ihr Schutzwert." volume="48" year="1996">Spitzer et al. 1996</bibRefCitation>
) because it is restricted to peat bogs. The Swiss habitat is completely different and can be characterized as a northern exposed subalpine Larici-Piceetum plant-association dominated by 
<taxonomicName id="E2981F8540A54961DA3CD47FE70E7C5A" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Larix" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Larix decidua" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="decidua">
<emphasis id="5CA9DA9D1DA900550DA8FBF433421FCB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Larix decidua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Mill. and 
<taxonomicName id="1D88CB51DAFD8C5D405A113B7B7B601E" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Picea" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Picea abies" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abies">
<emphasis id="7384DF7082920EF1422531666877FD8D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Picea abies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) H. Karst and interspersed 
<taxonomicName id="1685A68C5F0AB8EB847CFCBA085009FD" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus cembra" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cembra">
<emphasis id="20D9FF48473D5E535C5F9F942A4055EB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Pinus cembra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., 
<taxonomicName id="F1D25214F6FFA7085E17A83F4E25B638" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula pendula" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pendula">
<emphasis id="42FFB96D4FB245B54BCAE6BDABC13F77" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Betula pendula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Roth and 
<taxonomicName id="73BB329E4ED16DE5D15D96455AF3F34D" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Alnus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Alnus alnobetula" order="Fagales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alnobetula">
<emphasis id="9C9DA06ECE10600E5DD17D6CFB8AF2E5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Alnus alnobetula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Ehrh.) K. Koch are also present in the adjacent area. This biotope is located in a north-facing, steep avalanche gully at the bottom of which remaining snow masses may persist into early summer and provide unique microclimatic conditions. Furthermore, the most infested 
<taxonomicName id="5517380F5189ABD309DE5D818A7E3E7D" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ericaceae" genus="Rhododendron" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Rhododendron" order="Ericales" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="62ED38412F9EA8C22E4216286FC4C854" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Rhododendron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shrubs are often rather puny specimens, growing in very shady places and thus unable to produce flowers.
</paragraph>
